The paper discusses the complexity of the game of reconnaissance blind chess from a game theoretic perspective, tracking the proliferation of information sets from the perspective of selected canonical bot players in tournament play. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper evaluates RBC from an AI perspective, comparing different playing algorithms and providing cursory assessments of the various sensing and moving strategies, which suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the size of the game's information sets, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also provides complexity analysis, which suggests that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the various sensing and moving strategies, which suggests that it could belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
